                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d762">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">119.2/2999: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Frame</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Marriner</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-08-29T15:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 29, 1935—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 29—10:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>741. My 729, August 26, 10 a.m.<note n="87" xml:id="d762fn87">Not printed.</note>
                        Bargeton<note n="88" xml:id="d762fn88">Paul Bargeton, Chief of Political and
                        Commercial Affairs Section in the French Foreign Office.</note> informed me
                    this morning that after discussing the matter with the technical services and
                    the Prime Minister despite their entire willingness to be of assistance in every
                    way possible to maintain communications between our Legation in Addis Ababa and
                    Washington they did not feel inclined to grant permission for an American
                    cruiser to be stationed at Djibouti fearing the precedent this might create with
                    other countries who might ask for similar favors. Likewise, Bargeton pointed out
                    that in case of any outbreak of hostilities in which France should remain
                    neutral they could not permit the presence of any vessel of war of any power
                    within this harbor for more than 15 days. He expressed the Foreign Minister’s
                    regret at not being able to accede to our desire.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Marriner</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
